  // -- FAQ --
  faq: [
    { question: 'What types of toy worksheets can I create?', answer: 'You can generate a wide variety of toy-themed worksheets including size comparison activities with big-small sorting, counting toy collections with addition and subtraction, matching identical toys, shadow matching with toy silhouettes, word searches featuring toy vocabulary, coloring pages of favorite toys, find-and-count activities in toy scenes, more-or-less comparison exercises, odd-one-out puzzles, and bingo games with toy images.' },
    { question: 'Are the toy worksheets free to use?', answer: 'Yes, LessonCraftStudio lets you create and download toy-themed worksheets at no cost. Choose your preferred worksheet type, select the toys theme, customize settings like difficulty and number of items, and generate a printable PDF ready for your classroom or home learning session.' },
    { question: 'What age groups are toy worksheets suitable for?', answer: 'Toy worksheets are designed for children ages 3 through 9, covering preschool through third grade. Younger children benefit from coloring familiar toys and comparing sizes of teddy bears and blocks, while older students tackle multi-step math word problems with toy scenarios, measurement activities, data collection about toy preferences, and equal-sharing division readiness problems.' },
    { question: 'How do toy worksheets teach size comparison and measurement?', answer: 'Toy worksheets use familiar objects that children already understand intuitively to build formal comparison skills. Activities progress from simple big-small identification to ordering three or more objects by size, to measuring toys with non-standard units. Because children already know which of their toys is biggest, the worksheets formalize existing knowledge with academic vocabulary like taller, shorter, heavier, and lighter.' },
    { question: 'Can toy worksheets help children learn to count and do addition?', answer: 'Absolutely. Counting toy collections gives children a personally meaningful reason to practice one-to-one correspondence and cardinality. Addition problems like if you have six blocks and get three more make arithmetic feel like a natural extension of play. The high motivation children have toward toys translates directly into sustained attention for math practice.' },
    { question: 'How do toy worksheets support social-emotional skills?', answer: 'Many toy activities naturally involve sharing, taking turns, and cooperating. Worksheets that present these scenarios give children vocabulary and frameworks for navigating social situations during play. Activities about dividing toys fairly, taking turns with a shared game, and using words to resolve toy-related conflicts build the social-emotional competencies that make peer interactions successful.' },
    { question: 'Are toy worksheets just for fun or do they have real academic value?', answer: 'They have substantial academic value. Size comparison builds measurement foundations, counting collections develops number sense, sorting toys by multiple attributes strengthens classification skills used in science and math, and toy vocabulary expands descriptive language abilities. The fun factor is an asset, not a limitation, because motivated learners sustain attention longer and retain skills better.' },
    { question: 'Can toy worksheets be extended with hands-on activities?', answer: 'Toy worksheets are among the easiest to extend because the real objects are already in every home and classroom. After completing a size comparison worksheet, children can sort their actual toys by size. After counting collections on paper, they can count and graph their real toy inventory. This seamless paper-to-hands-on transition is a major advantage of the toy theme.' },
    { question: 'How do I print or download the toy worksheets?', answer: 'After customizing your worksheet, click the generate button to create a print-ready PDF. You can then download the file to your computer or use your browser\'s print function. All worksheets are formatted for standard letter and A4 paper sizes for easy printing at home or school.' },
    { question: 'How often should children complete toy worksheets?', answer: 'Two to four sessions per week works well for most children. Each session should last ten to twenty minutes depending on age. For a deeper thematic unit, dedicate a full week to toys, rotating through counting, comparison, sorting, and vocabulary worksheets daily. Always pair paper activities with real toy play to reinforce the connection between structured learning and imaginative exploration.' },
  ],

